ent with it mediating their effects on ommatidial polarity. CONCLUSIONS: The clonal phenotypes, time of requirement and regulation of four-jointed are consistent with it acting in ommatidial polarity determination as a second signal downstream of Notch, JAK/STAT and Wingless. Interestingly, it appears to act redundantly with unknown factors in this process, providing an explanation for the previous failure to identify a second signal.</api:text></api:field><api:field name="authors" type="person-list" display-name="Authors"><api:people><api:person><api:links><api:link type="elements/user" id="3495" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/users/3495"/></api:links><api:last-name>Zeidler</api:last-name><api:initials>MP</api:initials><api:first-names>MP</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>M</api:first-name><api:first-name>P</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names><api:addresses><api:address iso-country-code="US"><api:line type="full">Department of Genetics, Harvard Medical School, Boston, 02115, USA.</api:line></api:address></api:addresses></api:person><api:person><api:last-name>Perrimon</api:last-name><api:initials>N</api:initials><api:first-names>N</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>N</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person><api:person><api:links><api:link type="elements/user" id="1470" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/users/1470"/></api:links><api:last-name>Strutt</api:last-name><api:initials>DI</api:initials><api:first-names>DI</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>D</api:first-name><api:first-name>I</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person></api:people></api:field><api:field name="author-url" type="text" display-name="Link 1"><api:text>https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10607560</api:text></api:field><api:field name="doi" type="text" display-name="DOI"><api:text>10.1016/s0960-9822(00)80081-0</api:text><api:links><a